post_text:
Good Morning EB!
Here's a great resource should you need it:
Drive Up WiFi at New Jersey Libraries
WiFi access is crucial for New Jersey residents to work, study, and connect to important resources. Libraries are committed to bridging the digital divides in their communities by providing WiFi free of charge. The NJ State Library has compiled a map of NJ public libraries that provides details about how to connect to WiFi from outside of library buildings that are currently closed due to COVID-19: https://www.njstatelib.org/drive-up-wifi-at-new-jersey-libraries/
The map and other information on this page will be updated and available even after libraries reopen and things return to “normal.” We realize that COVID-19 reinforced the importance of collecting this information, but the issues around WiFi access are not unique to this crisis.

post_text:
A message from Michael Capobianco, EBPS Director of Child Nutrition, with information on meal distribution for the week of May 25, 2020:

The child nutrition department will continue to offer pre-ordered grab-and-go meals to all students next week.
Please be aware, meals will NOT be delivered on Monday, May 25, rather, they will be delivered on Tuesday, May 26.
Meal pick-up will be at the same select locations and times throughout the Township.
Each student will still receive enough meals for five days.
Meals will continue to be distributed at no cost to students. Grab-and-go meals will include both breakfast and lunch items.
As a reminder, parents/guardians must place an online order for grab-and-go meals for each eligible student in their household.
If you would like to participate in this meal plan, kindly complete this online order form by 5:00 p.m. on Thursday, May 21.
If you have any questions, please e-mail: childnutrition@ebnet.org.
For more information please visit the district website.

Thank you

post_text:
Good Morning EB!

Here's some Great News from the EBPS Academics Department:

The New Jersey State Division of Academics and Performance is pleased to announce that East Brunswick Township School District has been designated as a World Language model program for the 2020-2022 award period.

East Brunswick district will serve as a resource for other districts across the state and enable educators to explore exemplary practices in world language instruction and assessment.

Based upon documentation provided, site visitation, interviews with administrators, teachers, parents and students, East Brunswick has met all criteria to be named a Model Program for the 2020-2022 cohort.

Congratulations to Supervisor Mrs. Ruth Chang and the entire World Language Team!

Good Morning EB!

Based upon documentation provided, site visitation, interviews with administrators, teachers, parents and students, East Brunswick has met all criteria to be named a Model Program for the 2020-2022 cohort.

Congratulations to Supervisor Mrs. Ruth Chang and the entire World Language Team!

post_text:
April 14, 2020

Good Evening East Brunswick Community,

This is Victor Valeski, Superintendent of Schools.

I know better than anyone that our warmer weather draws us to be outside and I know we miss being around each other. I hope you understand that during this critical time of possible community transmission of the Coronavirus, I must keep our playgrounds and outdoor athletic facilities closed with the exception of our high school track. The track will remain open for public use as long as we can comply with social distancing standards.

This action is for everyone's safety and for our compliance with Governor Murphy's Executive Orders, issued during this pandemic.

Thank you all, in advance, for your cooperation.
text:
April 14, 2020

Good Evening East Brunswick Community,

This is Victor Valeski, Superintendent of Schools.

I know better than anyone that our warmer weather draws us to be outside and I know we miss being around each other. I hope you understand that during this critical time of possible community transmission of the Coronavirus, I must keep our playgrounds and outdoor athletic facilities closed with the exception of our high school track. The track will remain open for public use as long as we can comply with social distancing standards.

This action is for everyone's safety and for our compliance with Governor Murphy's Executive Orders, issued during this pandemic.

Thank you all, in advance, for your cooperation.

post_text: Good Morning EB - Good to see everyone pitching in to serve those on the front lines of this pandemic. Irwin School donated 100 dozen Krispy Kreme donuts to St. Peter’s University Hospital, Robert Wood Johnson Hospital and the East Brunswick police department recently. Parents, teachers, the Principal, family and friends of our students all contributed to the donation. We raised $500. The recipients were so grateful and said Irwin School was going to make a lot of people smile!

The United Nations has declared April 2, 2020 as World Autism Awareness Day.

Autism is one of the fastest-growing developmental disorders in the U.S. It now affects 1 in 59 children.

Wear something blue on April 2,202 in support of understanding and acceptance for people with autism. Please share your pictures on Twitter @EBPublicSchools.

post_text:
March 18, 2020 Message from Dr. Valeski, Superintendent.

Good Afternoon East Brunswick Community,

This is Victor Valeski, Superintendent of Schools.

By Governor Murphy’s Executive Order # 104, signed Monday, March 16, 2020,

“All public, private, and parochial preschool program premises, and elementary and secondary schools, including charter and renaissance schools, shall be closed to students beginning on Wednesday, March 18, 2020, and shall remain closed as long as this Order remains in effect.”

What that means is I do not a specific end date to our closure. Consequently, I am canceling all parent/teacher conferences scheduled March 24th-27th. As always, I encourage parents and guardians to email their children’s teachers to discuss individual progress or academic concerns.

I know this is a difficult time. I saw many of you on Tuesday during our Chromebook distribution at Churchill. With grit, determination and support for each other we will recover from this.

A message from EAST BRUNSWICK PUBLIC SCHOOLS

Good Evening East Brunswick Community,

This is Victor Valeski, Superintendent of Schools.

I know this a late call but it is an important one. Tonight, we have fielded countless calls and emails about our school closing...and I understand your concerns. We are aware of numerous social media posts that are inaccurate. As always, I wanted everyone to hear directly from me.

My move to close schools was precautionary. As of this evening at 9:45 PM, no East Brunswick Public School staff member or student has been suspected or tested for Coronavirus.

We will continue to work closely with the NJ Department of Health, NJ Department of Education and East Brunswick Township to coordinate our actions and recovery from this extremely stressful situation. Please remain confident that the entire East Brunswick team has the safety and security of all students, staff and community members as their top priority.

Good Evening East Brunswick School Community,

This is Victor Valeski, Superintendent of Schools. This evening our East Brunswick School Community suffered the tragic loss of one of our male, 8th grade Churchill Junior High School students in an accident on the frozen pond located at Civic Center Drive. Two other male Churchill students also fell through the ice but were able to self-rescue themselves.

Additional counseling support will be available throughout the day for both students and staff. Additionally, areas of support for students and staff have been established at all three of our secondary schools.

Please keep these students, their families, our first responders and the East Brunswick community in your thoughts tonight.

Kindergarten Registration is by appointment only. Please visit www.ebnet.org/register to schedule your appointment. All required forms and additional information can be found on the website. To assist us in planning for the upcoming school year, please register by April 30, 2020.

Registration takes place at the District Registration Office located in the Jon R. Kopko Administration Building at 760 Route 18, East Brunswick.

post_text: East Brunswick Public Schools along with the East Brunswick Municipal Alliance for Prevention of Drug and Alcohol Abuse, will hold a Parent University for the viewing of the documentary, “Angst,” highlighting the impact of anxiety on children. After the viewing, Dr. Allen Weg, of Stress & Anxiety Services of NJ will discuss, "Responding to Anxiety in School-Aged Children: A Primer for Parents," followed by a Q & A session. This event will be held Thursday, January 30th at 7 PM in the Media Center at the High School.

After the viewing, Dr. Allen Weg, of Stress & Anxiety Services of NJ will discuss, "Responding to Anxiety in School-Aged Children: A Primer for Parents," followed by a Q & A session. This event will be held Thursday, January 30th at 7 PM in the Media Center at the High School.

post_text: Pictured here is Alina of our “Middles to Littles” program at Hammarskjold Middle School. Middle school students are selected by their Language Arts teachers, based on their positive interactions and performance in school, to read to our Early Learning Academy students. Alina’s efforts were recognized recently by Dr. Michael Gaskell, Principal of Hammarskjold Middle School, Dr. Victor Valeski, Superintendent of East Brunswick Public Schools, Mr. AbdulSaleem Hasan, New Jersey Department of Education Assistant Commissioner - Field Services, and Mr. Kyle Anderson, Interim Middlesex County Superintendent of Schools who visited Hammarskjold this week. The Middles to Littles program is a collaborative effort between the Hammarskjold School Administrative team and the Community Programs Early Learning Academy. Middles to Littles is supported by the East Brunswick Education Foundation.

Our six talented East Brunswick students who represented our district in the orchestra. The students are:
Edwin Chao, Cello (11th grade)
Sally Lynch, Bass (11th grade)
Michael Shen, Violin (11th grade)
Michael Sun, Violin (11th grade)
Kelvin Zheng, Viola (12th grade)
Varun Mehrotra, Bass (11th grade)
Sponsor Teacher: Dr. Arvin Gopal, EBHS

The students spent full two days rehearsing in Atlantic City during the NJEA convention, which culminated with a concert on Friday, November 8th at Boardwalk Hall. They gave their final performance at NJPAC in Newark this past Sunday, November 17th. We are so proud of all their hard work and dedication!

All students and staff are safe and accounted for. The E.B.P.D. will communicate with District Administration any needs to modify other buildings' status.

post_text: A team of four students from Mr. Cohen’s AP Computer Science classes took home 1st place and a Raspsberry Pi on Friday, November 15, 2019. Rachel Ai, Archisa Bhattacharya, Michael Gorbunov, and Justin Yu, along with Mrs. Nesci, attended the CyberEncounters workshop sponsored by the NSF, the SANS Institute, and GirlsGoCyberstart, which was hosted by Brookdale Community College. Students and teachers attended a half-day workshop, where they learned how to use command line Linux, digital forensics, and cryptography tools. After lunch, 25 teams from high schools all around NJ competed to decrypt coded messages, find hidden information in photos, and uncover secrets the way computer hackers do. The competition was intense, but East Brunswick pulled out a win over Morristown High School by mere seconds. #EBforthewin
